{
  "type": "feature",
  "title": "Quick Pace Match Card — shadow at a target WPM with live tempo feedback",
  "description": "Build directly on iter 673's Reply Pacing Meter by adding a new Quick Practice Hub mini-card focused exclusively on speech tempo control. Many learners either rush nervously or speak too slowly when shadowing; this card turns WPM into the explicit goal.\n\nFlow:\n1. User opens the card and picks a target pace: Slow (≈110 WPM), Natural (≈150 WPM), or Fast (≈180 WPM). Default = Natural; remembered in localStorage key 'quick-pace-match-target'.\n2. Card fetches a short sentence (10–18 words) by reusing the existing shadow-sentence backend used by QuickShadowCard (call api.quickShadow / equivalent — no new endpoint needed). Difficulty propagates from the Hub's existing Difficulty selector.\n3. TTS plays the sentence at a rate mapped from the chosen target (slow=0.8, natural=1.0, fast=1.2) using useSpeechSynthesis.\n4. User taps Mic and shadows. useSpeechRecognition records start/end timestamps; on stop, compute spoken WPM = (recognized_word_count / elapsed_seconds) * 60. Also compute word-match accuracy (reuse normalizeText/computeAccuracy logic from QuickShadowCard).\n5. Result panel shows: a horizontal tempo gauge with the target band highlighted (±15 WPM tolerance), the user's WPM as a marker, a delta badge ('+22 WPM — too fast' / 'on pace ✓' / '-18 WPM — too slow'), and an accuracy % so users don't game the meter by mumbling.\n6. 'Try Again' replays same sentence; 'New Sentence' fetches another. Last 5 attempts are kept in component state and rendered as tiny WPM dots above the gauge so the user can see whether they are converging on the target band (mirrors sparkline UX of the Reply Pacing Meter).\n\nFiles:\n- frontend/src/components/QuickPaceMatchCard.tsx (new) — the card component, ≈200 lines, uses useSpeechSynthesis and useSpeechRecognition hooks already in the repo. No new API. Pure-function helpers (mapTargetToRate, computeWpm, classifyPace, tolerance band) exported for testing.\n- frontend/src/components/QuickPracticeHub.tsx — import the new card and register it in the Speaking tab section with key 'pace-match', emoji 🎯, title 'Pace Match', short blurb 'Shadow at a target speaking speed.' Add to favorites-eligible list (uses the existing useFavorites hook automatically via hub registration).\n- frontend/src/__tests__/QuickPaceMatchCard.test.tsx (new) — unit tests for the helper functions: computeWpm(words, seconds) edge cases (0 seconds → 0, normal case), classifyPace(spoken, target, tolerance=15) returns 'slow'|'on'|'fast' boundaries, mapTargetToRate('slow'|'natural'|'fast') returns expected playbackRate values. Plus a render smoke test asserting the three target buttons appear and clicking one persists to localStorage.\n\nNo backend/schema/migration changes. Differentiation from existing cards: QuickShadowCard measures accuracy only; QuickConnectedSpeech focuses on linking; QuickThoughtGroup focuses on phrasing pauses; QuickFillerReduction targets fillers — none currently treats target WPM as a primary, selectable goal with per-attempt tempo trend feedback.",
  "files_to_modify": [
